    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1925-03-18T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1925-03-18T08:00:00-05:00" n="13"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d13">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A12/45: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bancroft</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-03-18T22:00:00+09:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 18, 1925—10 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 18—10:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>51. Two Tokyo newspapers today carry London despatch which says: <pb facs="0135"
                        n="9" xml:id="pg_9"/>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Following the failure of the Geneva Protocol,<note n="14"
                                xml:id="d13fn14">On March 12 the British Secretary of State for
                                Foreign Affairs stated to the Council of the League of Nations that
                                his Government could not accept the protocol or recommend its
                                acceptance to the other Governments of the Empire. See Great
                                Britain, Cmd. 2368, Miscellaneous No. 5 (1925).</note> the
                            President’s announcement of his intention to call another conference
                            evidently follows course of action agreed upon by Chamberlain and
                            Kellogg when they came to an understanding just before the latter left
                            London”.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Despatch refers to President’s alleged decision to proceed with conference even
                    if some powers refuse to take part, as being aimed at France in London’s
                    opinion.</p>
                <p>The chief aide to the Minister of the Navy said today that Japan was persuaded
                    that conversations had taken place between the United States and Great Britain
                    before the first Washington Conference (1922) and in guarded reference to above
                    report gave impression that those conversations were regarded by Japanese as
                    very significant.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bancroft</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
